\f1\b0\fs40 \cf0 Preheat oven to 350 degrees F.\
\
In a bowl whisk egg yolks and 1/2 cup sugar until it is a pale yellow, set aside. In a medium {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/saucepan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 saucepan}} heat heavy cream, over low heat, to just a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/boil/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 boil}}. Slowly add cream to yolks, whisking constantly to avoid curdling. Transfer yolk mixture back to saucepan. Cook until {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/custard/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 custard}} thickens and coats the back of a spoon, then add vanilla and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/whiskey/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 whiskey}}. Keep custard over low heat to keep warm, but do not allow eggs to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/curdle/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 curdle}}. In a clean medium bowl whisk the egg whites, remaining 1 tablespoon of sugar, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cream-of-tartar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cream of tartar}} and salt until stiff peaks form. Drop heaping spoonfuls of the meringue onto a parchment lined baking sheet. Bake 8 minutes, or until peaks are golden. To assemble, divide custard into 4 shallow bowls. Top each with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/meringue/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 meringue}} peak, sprinkle with berries and powdered sugar.\
